div.head: SPAINE.
div.p: SPaine beeing greater then France, & leſſer then Germanie, is environed with the great [Ocean] and the [Mediterranean] ſea, except on the north-eaſt ſyde, for there it is cononeat with France, from the which it is deuyded by by the monmaines called the [Pireates], it is now one entire monarchie but in former ryme hath bene denyded into fourtęene Kingdomes. By authors thus recounted vid. The old and new Caſhlia, Leon, Arragea, Catalonia, Nanarre, Aſturia, Granada], Valentia, Toledo, Galicia], Murcia, Cordona, Portagal, & Algarbe. Spaine albeit it bee not in all places manured becauſe of the ſtonyeſſe of fundry parres thereof, yet is it far more fertil then Africa, & in very many places it yeildeth aboundantly whatſoever is neceſſary for the vſe of man, As very faire VVheat, Rice, VVyne, Oyle, Hony, Saffran, Sugar, Limones, Capers, Citrons, Orenges, Pomgranades, & other fruytes. Roſmary groweth there in the fieldes in ſuch plenty that it ſerueth for fuel. It hath alſo great ſhore of beaſtes both wild & tame, & yeildeth horſes of ſuch ſwiftnes that it was ſaid of them in old tyme (as a prouerb) that they were engendred of the wynde.It hath alſo diuers mynes, as of Gold, Siluer, Copper, Tin, Iron, and Lead, & gold is not only found in mynes, but euen in ſaud on the ſydes of the riuevr [Taye]. In fundry maritime places it yeildeth great ſhore of Salt. The ayre is pure and helthful, it is little ſnhieƈt vnto tempeſtes, & is free from foule & contagious miſtes. According to a vulgar ſaying three thinges in Spaine are for the rarety of them very memorable, to wit, A bridge ouer the which water runneth, which vſually runneth vnder bridges, enrending therebythe aquaduƈt of Segouia. A towneeńuyroned with fyre, meaningMadrid, the walles whereof are of flint. And a bridge whereon ten thowſand beaſtes are continually paſtured, which is venderſtood by the riuer Guaɖuana, which running into the earth hydeth it ſelf the length of ſeauen leagues, & then coming footh againe holɖeth his courſe as before.
